The documentation of adding a new user in Crowd leads to a misunderstanding and makes the customer thinking that Crowd will send an email when a new user is added:
{code}
  (info) If you have configured an email server and a notification template, Crowd will send the user an email notification about their new password.
{code} 

It should be updated and state that Crowd will send the email when the user request it in "forgotten password" field.

This feature request is regarding crowd understanding wildcards characters when authorizing access to a Subversion repository.
It would be easier if wildcards could be used to provide group/user access to certain directories.

An example given by a customer:

[<REPO>:/branches]
@SVN-<REPO>-Dev = r
@SVN-<REPO>-BE = rw

[<REPO>:/branches/*/*]
@SVN-<REPO>-Dev = rw
@SVN-<REPO>-BE = rw

The idea is give *read and write* permission just to the directories under the branches directory, but just read only permission on the main directory (branches). However the star character used to represent the directories under branches, is not recognized as a wildcard character by crowd.

Errors such as these:
{code}
INFO [directory.ldap.util.DirectoryAttributeRetriever] Unsafe or Blank attribute value for attribute <givenName>: ' '

INFO [directory.ldap.util.DirectoryAttributeRetriever] Unsafe or Blank attribute value for attribute <sn>: ' '.

ERROR [[Catalina].[localhost].[/].[default]] Servlet.service() for servlet default threw exception
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: Not a valid attribute string value:ou$$@\m/@,improper usage of backslash
{code}
Should have more information, without setting the class to TRACE. Example:
{code}
INFO: Unsafe or Blank attribute value for attribute <givenName>. Context: <cn=usertest,dc=example,dc=com>. Attribute was skipped.

WARN: Not a valid attribute string value <ou$$@\m/@>, improper usage of backslash. Attribute: <sn>. Context: <cn=usertest,dc=example,dc=com>. User was skipped.
{code}
It is important to have a Context, Attribute Name, and Attribute Value in a WARN/ERROR message, so that it's easier for administrators to identify the user/group in LDAP that is causing the issue

{panel:title=Note|bgColor=#f4cb42|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#f4cb42}


Please note that since 3.0.0 release Crowd can be run in Data Center mode which supports Clustering. This is the supported way of running Crowd in cluster.
{panel}
 

Crowd isn't supported in a clustered environment (-CWD-1053-), but it can work in some configurations.

After configuring Crowd in a Tomcat cluster ([Clustering/Session Replication HOW-TO|http://tomcat.apache.org/tomcat-6.0-doc/cluster-howto.html]) and pointing all instances at a common database, this is a tracking bug for the remaining issues.
 * Crowd's {{web.xml}} does not mark it as {{<distributable/>}}
 * Hibernate's second-level and query caches are enabled, so administration changes to settings are not communicated between instances
 * Password reset tokens are not distributed; a password can only be reset against same instance that sent the email
 * Synchronisation is not aware of clustering; any cached directories will fail when synchronisation runs at the same time

Crowd logs a deprecation warning on startup:

{noformat}
WARN [beans.factory.config.CustomEditorConfigurer] Passing PropertyEditor instances into CustomEditorConfigurer is deprecated: use PropertyEditorRegistrars or PropertyEditor class names instead. Offending key [org.codehaus.xfire.service.ServiceFactory; offending editor instance: org.codehaus.xfire.spring.editors.ServiceFactoryEditor@dabb176
{noformat}

This is due to {{customEditors.xml}} in XFire.

Request URIs:
{noformat}
DELETE /user/{username}/session
DELETE /user/{username}/session?exclude={token}
{noformat}

shall delete all sessions maintained for the specified user. This effectively logs them out everywhere.

If an exclude parameter is provided, presumably using the token in the current browser, then that session (if it exists) is excluded. If it does not exist, there is no error.

Response status:
* {{404 Not Found}} - if the user does not exist
* {{205 Reset Content}} - otherwise (and no body content is returned)

If you insist on maintain the terrible URI formats for user resources, they'll have to look like this:

{noformat}
DELETE /user/session?username={username}
DELETE /user/session?username={username}&exclude={token}
{noformat}
